HEADWORD: Agallochum
<hw>A*gal"lo*chum</hw> <pr>(⟦adot⟧*g⟦acr⟧l"l⟦osl⟧*k⟦ucr⟧m)</pr>,
}</mhw> <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <grk>a`ga`llochon</grk>, of Eastern
origin: cf. Skr. <ets>aguru</ets>, Heb. pl.
<ets>ah⟦amac⟧l⟦imac⟧m</ets>.]</ety> <def>A soft, resinous wood
(<spn>Aquilaria Agallocha</spn>) of highly aromatic smell, burnt by the
orientals as a perfume. It is called also <altname>agalwood</altname>
and <altname>aloes wood</altname>. The name is also given to some other
species.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

